SIMPLE: proverbial
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Proverbial
<hw>Pro*ver"bi*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>proverbialis</ets>: cf. F. <ets>proverbial</ets>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>Mentioned or comprised in a proverb; used as a proverb;
hence, commonly known; <as>as, a <ex>proverbial</ex> expression; his
meanness was <ex>proverbial</ex>.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In case of excesses, I take the German <qex>proverbial</qex> cure,
by a hair of the same beast, to be the worst.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W.
Temple.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to proverbs; resembling a
proverb.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧A <xex>proverbial</xex> obscurity.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Sir T. Browne.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Proverbialism</ent>⟦br⟧
